# <type>[optional scope]: <description>
#
# [optional body]
#
# [optional footer(s)]

# feat:     A new feature
# fix:      A bug fix
# docs:     Documentation only changes
# style:    Code style changes (formatting, missing semi-colons, etc.)
# refactor: Code change that neither fixes a bug nor adds a feature
# perf:     Performance improvements
# test:     Adding or updating tests
# build:    Changes to build system or dependencies
# ci:       Changes to CI/CD configuration
# chore:    Other changes that don't modify src or test files
# revert:   Reverts a previous commit
#
# For breaking changes:
# 1. Add '!' after type/scope: feat(module)!: description
# 2. Include 'BREAKING CHANGE:' in body or footer
# 3. Explain what breaks and how to migrate
#
# Guidelines:
# - Use present tense: "add feature" not "added feature"
# - Use imperative mood: "change" not "changes"
# - First line max 72 characters
# - Body wraps at 72 characters
# - Separate subject from body with blank line
# - Reference issues/PRs in footer: "Fixes #123" or "Closes #456"
# - Keep commits focused on a single change
#
# feat(ec2): add support for instance metadata options
# fix(cloudfront): correct CORS header configuration
# docs(readme): update usage examples for VPC module
# refactor(s3): simplify bucket policy structure
# feat(eip)!: change output variable names for consistency
#
# BREAKING CHANGE: Output variable names have changed.
# - `instance_id` is now `id`
# - `instance_public_ip` is now `public_ip`
